   "regular-body" : "<p>You&rsquo;ll be surprised to see me getting all excited about <a href=\"http://www.gameagent.com/store/aspyr/pd/productID.176431500/pgm.78347700\">the Mac port</a> of a <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Star_Wars:_Knights_of_the_Old_Republic\">nine year old game</a> making it <a href=\"http://store.steampowered.com/app/32370/\">on to Steam</a>. But there&rsquo;s a very good reason for it: it means the Aspyr&rsquo;s <a href=\"http://itunes.apple.com/us/app/star-wars-knights-old-republic/id416608891?mt=12\">unfortunate partnership with the Mac App Store</a> is being reconsidered. The Mac App Store (MAS) is an awful platform for gamers: no special deals and promotions throughout the year, no achievements, no social gaming, no automatic updating (I think?). Steam is where gamers want to be: it&rsquo;s where our friends are, it&rsquo;s where the best deals are, it&rsquo;s got autoupdate, and it lets me swap games around so they don&rsquo;t take up too much space on my paltry hard drive. If Aspyr is playing around with bringing games on to Steam &ndash; and I really don&rsquo;t see LucasArts putting pressure on them to bring their almost-decade-old game to Steam &ndash; there&rsquo;s <a href=\"http://www.gameagent.com/store/aspyr/DisplayCategoryProductListPage/categoryID.44906100\">a whole bunch of fantastic Mac games</a> which might be making their way to my favourite game store, at a price I might be able to afford. I&rsquo;m hoping for more.</p>",
